article.headline: Idaho State 66, Maine 57
article.story: MILWAUKEE (AP) -- Senior guard David Schroeder scored 22 points and became Idaho State's all-time 3-point shooting leader in a 66-57 victory over Maine Tuesday in a consolation game of the CBE Classic. Schroeder, who also had nine rebounds, shot 8-of-12 from the floor and 3-of-7 from 3-point range for the Bengals, who never trailed as they gave first-year coach Joe O'Brien his first victory. Senior guard Akbar Abdul-Ahad added 10 points for Idaho State (1-1). O'Brien nearly had his first victory Monday, when the Bengals almost upset the 16th-ranked Marquette before falling 59-56 in overtime. O'Brien came to the Bengals after 13 seasons and a 313-117 record in the junior college ranks, including three national titles at Southwestern Iowa Community College. Schroeder now has 138 3-pointers, topping the career mark of 136 by Jeff Gardner from 2003-05. Mark Socoby led Maine (0-3) with 24 points, including five 3-pointers. Jon Sheets added nine points, including a 3-pointer that narrowed the Bengals' lead to 63-57 with 34.8 seconds left. It was as close as the Black Bears would get. Maine senior guard Kevin Reed injured his right knee in a scramble with 12:47 to go in the first half. Reed, who sat out the 2005-06 season as a medical redshirt, fell and immediately grabbed his knee. After several minutes, he was helped off the court and sat at the end of the Maine bench where he received medical attention. He did not return in the second half. Idaho State opened with a 17-3 run capped by two 3-pointers by Austin Kilpatrick and one by Matt Stucki. A 3-pointer by Logan Kinghorn put the Bengals ahead 41-24 with 14:31 left, and they maintained a double-digit lead until Maine got the lead under 10 points in the final minute.
